      "source_hash": "90276921add4d9fdda4daaac88e96bd00e97fb654c60bdc3fcd75cc57b0b5677",
      "text": "# The Antikythera Mechanism\n\nThe Antikythera mechanism is an ancient Greek hand-powered orrery, often\ndescribed as the oldest known analog computer. It was retrieved from the sea\nin 1901 from a shipwreck off the coast of the Greek island of Antikythera,\nand is dated to roughly 150–100 BC.\n\nThe device consists of at least 30 meshing bronze gears housed in a wooden\ncase roughly the size of a shoebox. By turning a hand crank, the user could\nadvance a pointer across a dial showing the position of the Sun and Moon in\nthe zodiac, the phase of the Moon, and the dates of solar and lunar eclipses\npredicted by the Saros cycle. A separate dial tracked the four-year cycle of\nthe Olympiad and other Panhellenic games.\n\nThe mechanism's sophistication was not matched in the surviving record until\nthe astronomical clocks of medieval Europe, more than a thousand years later.\nIts gear-cutting precision implies an established workshop tradition, yet no\ncomparable device or workshop has been found.\n\nDerek de Solla Price published the first detailed scientific study in 1974,\nusing X-ray imaging to count gear teeth. The Antikythera Mechanism Research\nProject, beginning in 2005, used microfocus X-ray computed tomography to read\ninscriptions hidden inside the corroded fragments — effectively a user's\nmanual engraved on the device's plates. The inscriptions suggest the device\nmay have originated in Corinth or its colonies, possibly linking it to the\nschool of Archimedes in Syracuse.\n",
      "unit_id": "unit-0001"
    }
  ],
